<oauth_oidc_misconfiguration_verification>
<validity_requirements>
For an OAuth/OIDC misconfiguration claim to be VALID, you must independently verify:

1. EXPLOITABLE WEAKNESS
   - OAuth flow has exploitable vulnerability
   - NOT: Just poor practices without exploitation
   - Check: Can you steal tokens or impersonate users?

2. TOKEN/CODE THEFT OR BYPASS
   - Can obtain tokens/codes belonging to others
   - NOT: Your own tokens (that's normal)
   - Check: Can you get victim's access token?

3. REDIRECT_URI MANIPULATION
   - Can redirect auth flow to attacker domain
   - NOT: Strict validation preventing redirect
   - Check: Does token/code go to your server?
</validity_requirements>

<independent_control_tests>
YOU MUST DESIGN YOUR OWN TESTS. Do not reproduce the reporter's tests.

TEST 1: TOKEN THEFT OR BYPASS
Purpose: Verify OAuth flow can be exploited
Steps:
1. Test redirect_uri manipulation to attacker domain
2. Check for token leakage (missing state, fragment)
3. Test PKCE bypass if applicable
4. Verify token/code can be captured

TEST 2: REDIRECT_URI VALIDATION
Purpose: Verify redirect_uri not properly validated
Steps:
1. Try: redirect_uri=https://evil.com
2. Try bypass: redirect_uri=https://trusted.com@evil.com
3. Try subdomain: redirect_uri=https://evil.trusted.com
4. Verify code/token delivered to attacker
</independent_control_tests>

<validity_decision_matrix>
| Weakness | Token Theft Possible | Reproducible | Decision |
|----------|---------------------|--------------|----------|
| Open redirect_uri | Yes | Consistent | VULNERABLE |
| Missing state | CSRF possible | Consistent | VULNERABLE |
| Strict validation | No | N/A | NOT VULNERABLE |
| PKCE enforced | Partial | Limited | INVESTIGATE |
</validity_decision_matrix>

<common_false_positive_patterns>
REJECT if you observe:
- Strict redirect_uri allowlist enforced
- State parameter properly implemented
- PKCE required and validated
- Token binding prevents theft
- Only theoretical weakness without PoC
</common_false_positive_patterns>
</oauth_oidc_misconfiguration_verification>
